value.value: Skeletal tissue that is avascular tubular mineralized matrix, primarily made of dentine that is deposited by odontoblasts that are excluded from the matrix; develops from pre-dentine tissue.
Sesamoid that develops within a tendon, distal to an articulation or joint.
Replacement element that forms as a replacement of a ligament.
Chondrogenic element that is composed of cartilage during development and has the potential to become replaced by another tissue.
Sesamoid that develops within a ligament, distal to an articulation or joint.
Dermal bone of pectoral girdle that is dorsal to and articulates with the cleithrum.

definition.value: In sarcopterygians; analogous in position to postcleithrum in actinopterygians.

value.value: Fin that is an unpaired fin located in the sagittal plane of the organism.
Median fin that is located posterior to the anus.
The caudal fin is the most posterior median fin. It is composed of a complex of modified centra and modified neural and hemal arches and spines.
Median fin skeleton that is located posterior to the anus.
Median fin skeleton supporting the caudal fin.
Median fin skeleton located on the dorsal surface of the organism.
Postcranial axial skeleton that is unpaired and located on the sagittal plane of the organism.
Skeletal subdivision of dermal bones that may include the anterolateral plate (AL), the spinal process (Sp), and anteroventral plate (AV) and other dermal bones that are part of the pectoral girdle.

definition.value: A scapular complex is described in placoderms (Goujet and Young, 1995).

value.value: Dermal bone that is rod-like, formed and usually contained in a fin membrane, and jointed to or adjacent to distal radials. Lepidotrichia are formed from paired hemitrichia surrounding actinotrichia. There are usually two more lepidotrichia than distal radials.

definition.value: Need to review develops_from relationship to actinotrichia. Lepidotrichia require actinotrichia for development, but develops_from may not be appropriate relationship.  See Zhang et al 2010 for details.  doi:10.1038/nature09137

value.value: Lepidotrichium that is part of the pelvic fin skeleton.
Lepidotrichium that is part of the caudal fin skeleton.
Lepidotrichium that is part of the pectoral fin skeleton.

definition.value: Each pectoral lepidotrichium may be unsegmented (e.g., spine), segmented but unbranched (e.g., leading ray) or segmented and branched. Definition of lepidotrichium by Schultze and Arratia (1989: 217). For additional information about lepidotrichia see Arratia et al. 2001 and Arratia 2008.

value.value: Lepidotrichium that is part of the anal fin skeleton.
Lepidotrichium that is part of the dorsal fin skeleton.

Paired fin that is a bilaterally paired anterior outgrowth located high on the side of the animal, not far behind the orbit, with the posterior extremity corresponding with the expected posterior end of the branchial region.

definition.value: Suprabranchial fins are anterior outgrowths from the cephalothorax of thelodonts. Typically scale covered. They do not appear to contain skeletal tissues or elements.

value.value: Anatomical projection that is composed of bone or cartilage tissue.
Anatomical surface that is part of a skeletal element and articulates with another skeletal element.

definition.value: Not necessarily part of a joint.

value.value: Bony projection (peduncle) that is located on the posterior portion of the ilium, posterior to the acetabulum.
Second most proximal phalanx in manual or pedal digits.
Posterior projection of the interclavicle that extends betwen and sometimes beyond the clavicles.
Facet of scapulocoracoid with which the pectoral fin radial(s) articulates. Facet of scapulocoracoid with which the pectoral fin radial(s) articulates. Based on Goujet and Young (1995).

definition.value: Should be part of some joint.

value.value: Phalanx of the 7th pedal digit.
Distinct notch ventral to the glenoid.
A bony process at the distal margin of the acetabulum formed by the ischium and/or the ischial peduncle of the ilium.
Region of the ilium posterior and dorsal to the acetabulum.
The posterior of the two coracoid elements found in basal tetrapods. Corresponds directly to the 'coracoid' of synapsids.
Dorsal fin located posterior to the anterior dorsal fin.
A posteriorly directed bony projection from the ilium that is the attachment site of the iliofibularis muscle (see Sumida, 1997).
Lateral expansion of the parasphenoid.
Soft tissue sheath covering the hemipenis.
Facet to accommodate the radius on the distal end of the humerus.
Hinge in the skull skeleton to allow for kinetic movement of different parts.
Anatomical projection in the distal region of the femur.
Soft tissue notch/opening lying on a spiracle.
Anatomical projection in the posterior/distal region of the femur.
Rib located anterior to the sacral region.
Rib located in the trunk (ribcage) area (i.e. excluding cervical and caudal axial series.
Extratemporal bone: Skull bone in the posterior half of the cranium, bordering the squamosal and opercular.
The distinctive arrangement of four to ten spikes on the tails of stegosaurid dinosaurs. These spikes are believed to have been a defensive measure against predators.

The arrangement of spikes originally had no distinct name; the term Thagomizer was coined in 1982 by cartoonist Gary Larson in his comic 'The Far Side', and thereafter became gradually adopted as an informal term within scientific circles, research, and education.
The medial surface of the iliac blade. Origin site of the iliofemoralis internus muscle and its homologues.
The region of the pubis posterior to the acetabulum.

definition.value: In some non-avian reptile this terminology refers to a distinct rear facing process of the pubis. In avians and some closely related theropod taxa this term is used to denote the pubis itself which has been rotated to face backwards.

value.value: Broad, convex expansion of the coracoid bone below the level of the glenoid. Based on Romer 1956.
A type of pectoral fin in which the endoskeletal elements have a main axis that runs through the center of the fin. This creates a bilaterally symmetrical fin. (Modified from Kardong 2012).

definition.value: Is homologous to the tetrapod limb.

value.value: Depression on the ventreal side of the femoral head. Associated with the pubioischiofemoralis externus muscle.
